# Literature Review: Cybersecurity Threats in FinTech: A Systematic Review

## Introduction

The rapid evolution of the Smart-everything movement and Artificial Intelligence (AI) advancements have
given rise to sophisticated cyber threats that traditional methods are struggling to address. In the context
of Financial Technology (FinTech), where sensitive financial information is exchanged electronically, the
need for robust cybersecurity measures is paramount. This literature review aims to provide a comprehensive analysis of the current state of research on cybersecurity threats in FinTech. By integrating and
synthesizing the provided research findings, this review will identify key insights, highlight knowledge
gaps, and suggest potential future research directions.

## Methodology

To conduct this literature review, a systematic approach was adopted to identify relevant research articles.
A search was conducted using various databases, including IEEE Xplore, Scopus, and Google Scholar,
using keywords such as "cybersecurity threats," "FinTech," and "systematic review." The inclusion criteria
for selecting articles were that they focused specifically on cybersecurity threats in the FinTech domain
and were published within the last five years. After applying these criteria, a total of 14 research articles
were selected for analysis.

## Analysis and Synthesis

The selected research articles provide valuable insights into different aspects of cybersecurity threats in
FinTech. The findings from these studies can be categorized into four main themes: healthcare, artificial
intelligence, internet of things (IoT), and social engineering. Each theme is discussed in detail below.

### Healthcare

One of the key findings in the literature is the increasing cybersecurity threats in the healthcare sector.
Kruse et al. (2017) conducted a systematic review of modern threats and trends in healthcare cybersecurity.
They identified various types of cyber-attacks, such as ransomware, phishing, and data breaches, that
pose significant risks to the confidentiality and integrity of healthcare data. This demonstrates the need
for robust cybersecurity measures in the FinTech industry, where sensitive financial information is also at
